    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">How to Choose the Right Course for Your Child</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The best course depends on three things: your child's age, their current English level, and how they learn best.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">For ages 3-6: Keep it fun and short</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">At this age, attention spans are short and play is the main way kids learn. Look for courses with 25-minute lessons, lots of visual content, and teachers who use songs, games, and movement. Novakid and See Guru both do this well.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">For ages 7-10: Build a routine</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Kids this age benefit from regular lesson times and a structured curriculum. They can handle 30-minute sessions and start doing short homework assignments between lessons. Cambly Kids and VIPKid both offer the consistency that works for this age group.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">For ages 11-15: Focus on conversation and confidence</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Teenagers need to practice speaking more than anything else. They already know basic grammar from school. What they lack is confidence and real conversation practice. See Guru and Cambly Kids both emphasize live speaking, which is what matters most at this stage.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Common Questions</h2>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">How many lessons per week does my child need?</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Two to three lessons per week is the sweet spot for most kids. One lesson is not enough to build momentum. Five lessons is overkill and can lead to burnout. Consistency matters more than volume.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Should I choose group or private lessons?</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Private lessons are better for beginners who need patient, individual attention. Group lessons work well once your child can hold a basic conversation and would benefit from peer interaction. Some kids thrive in groups, others freeze up. You know your child best.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">Are online English courses safe for kids?</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">All the platforms listed here have safety measures in place: vetted teachers, parental dashboards, and lesson recordings you can review. Still, we recommend sitting in on the first few lessons and checking the recordings periodically, especially for younger children.</p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold mt-8 mb-3">What if my child does not like the tutor?</h3>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Switch tutors. Every platform on this list lets you change teachers at no extra cost. A good tutor-student match is the single biggest factor in whether your child keeps learning. Do not stick with a tutor your child dislikes just because you already booked lessons.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4">Our Pick</h2>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">For most families, <strong>See Guru</strong> offers the best balance of teaching quality, price, and flexibility. Live 1-on-1 lessons with tutors who specialize in kids, starting at $8 per session, is hard to beat. If you want a curriculum-first approach with certified teachers, Novakid is a strong second choice.</p>
    <p class="text-slate-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The most important thing is to start. Kids who begin learning English early have a huge advantage, and the right course makes the process feel natural instead of forced. Try a free trial lesson with any of these platforms and see how your child responds.</p>

